text: During his 1927 solo Atlantic flight Charles Lindbergh actually got so sleep deprived that while flying through a very foggy area he started seeing ghosts and apparitions in his airplane that were encouraging him and giving him navigation advice.

He also said he saw phantom islands that disappeared into mist as he approached them and ghost ships in the sea. 55 hours no sleep. But he did believe the apparitions in the airplane were actual entities and not just hallucinations, he kept it secret for years after the flight.

Another example of British Deep State 5D chess humor: the Russian cruiser "Aurora" was the instigator of both the February and October revolution and the first ship to wave the red communist flag, it fired the shot that signified the start of the assault of the Winter Palace.

Dmitry Galkovsky actually speculates both of them are a reference to a book by British early science fiction writer George Griffith who had a 1893 book where Russia is destroyed in a revolution against the Tsar and there's an airship called "Ariel" that saves the revolutionaries.

In China the British handed the Chiang Kai-shek government a cruiser also named "Aurora", it became the flagship of the Chinese Navy and immediately went over to the side of the communists. Its captain graduated in the British Royal Navy College, afterwards they made him admiral.

The inspiration behind Orwell's "Newspeak" and Gene Wolfe's Ascian language in BoTNS is Charles Kay Ogden's 850 word "BASIC English" that was tested out in the USSR. But the person who promoted "BASIC English" in Soviet military academies was Ivy Low, a friend of H. G. Wells.

They actually read Joyce texts translated into BASIC English on the radio and tried to turn it into a real thing, a language for the underclass. The Wiki page for "BASIC English" is that the 850 words are now used as a beginner's English vocabulary for English students in Asia.

People actually accused Wolfe of Ascian ("one without shadow", people living on the Equator) being a pun on Asians and that it was a polemic against Chinese communism brainwashing ppl into robots he made due to his Korean War experience. But he's optimistic if you read the book.

Aurora is the Roman goddess of the dawn that flies across the sky in the morning. And in Shakespeare's "The Tempest" Ariel is also a flying spirit whose name is a play on the word "aerial". So the entire thing is again multilayered and complicated, with various levels of meaning.
